{"id":14881713,"mediaExerciseId":"6bc5fa59-2b7e-461f-9e5e-72d3401ed3fc","exerciseName":"3","chapterName":"20","chapterTitle":"Credit and Inventory Management","groupId":612458,"groupTitle":"Critical Thinking Questions","isPremium":true,"sectionName":null,"sectionTitle":null,"pageNumber":700,"solutions":[{"id":6041773,"modifiedOn":"2021-01-01T00:00:00.000000","steps":[{"columns":[{"text":"In this problem, we need to explain the costs associated with carrying receivables, costs that arise when a credit is not granted to a customer, and also, we need to say how is called the costs for different levels of receivables. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":1},{"columns":[{"text":" The carrying costs associated with granting credit inculdes the required return on receivables, the losses from bad debts and the costs of managing credit and credit collections. \n","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":2},{"columns":[{"text":"The costs associated with not approving a credit are called opportunity costs and represent the extra potential profit that the firm loses because it has not sold the goods on credit. For example, if the company approved the credit, the buyer would buy a larger quantity of goods, and it is this difference between the quantity sold on credit and without credit  is the potential profit. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":3},{"columns":[{"text":"The sum of the costs for different levels of receivables are carrying costs. ","images":{"latex":null,"additional":null},"hasInvalidKatex":false,"isTextOnly":true}],"isResult":false,"stepNumber":4}],"rating":0,"solutionUuid":"2d1d19df-ea10-4d40-aa23-5c4470dbf972","editorVersion":2,"answeredOn":null,"ratingCount":null,"solutionOrder":null,"totalSteps":4}],"textbook":{"authors":"Br